{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_guildenstern_ver01/data/sn83016586/00542865167/1930090501/0299.xml":{"full_text":"Mahnomen Pioneer\nj z\nVolume 26\nWASHINGTON\nCORRESPONDENCE\nBankers and Capitalists Rule Amer-\nica According to Former Am-\nbassador Gerard\nAccording to former Ambassador\nJames W. Gerard fifty-nine Amer\nicans rule America. He does not in\nclude in the list the President of\nthe United States or even a Senator.\nThe only Cabinet officer mentioned\nis Secretary of the Treasury Mellon.\nMr. Gerard believes that real power\nin America rests with bankers and\ncapitalists and his list is made up\nof men who have great\nwealth at their command\nand \u201cwho rule by virtue of their\nability.\u201d Gerard reverts to the old\nphilosophy that it takes money to\nmake the mare go. As for his list\u2014\nwell it is additional proof of the\npre-war suspicion that Gerard is an\nimaginative sort of a good fellow.\nPennsylvania Improves\nFor generations Pennsylvania\ncould be counted upon to obey its\nmasters of politics. But independ\nent thought and an improved class\nof statesmenship have produced\ngood results in recent years. Vare\ncame very nearly turning the Key\nstone State back into its old politi\ncal ways, and Grundy bobbed up\nrepresenting organized business.\nThe recent decision of the Supreme\nCourt of Pennsylvania in refusing\nthe pleas of some of the old political\nelements to count Gifford Pinchot\nout of the nomination for Governor\nis another victory for the people of\nPennsylvania, who are now certain\nto elect pinch-hitter Pinchot for\ntheir next Governor. With Senator\nReed in the Senate and Secretary of\nLabor Davis scheduled to join him\nas a colleague this Winter the grand\nold State will have as strong a trio\nof official leaders as any State in\nthe Union. No reasonable person\ncould find very much fault with\nPinchot, Reed and Davis.\nKellogg on World Court\nIn Washington where former\nSecretary of State Frank B. Kellogg\nis better known than even out in\nhis home State of Minnesota there\nis genuine satisfaction over the fact\nthat he is likely to become a judge\nof the World Court to complete the\nterm left vacant by Charles Evans\nHughes, who resigned to become\nChief Justice of the United States.\nKellogg has been one of the out\nstanding world factors in behalf of\ntightening up the methods of gov\nernments to prevent them from go\ning to war.\nDenies Prosperity Talk\nA few days ago a Pittsburgh news\npaper correspondent telegraphed\nthe world and the newspapers\nthereof a very optimistic statement\nalleged to have been made by An\ndrew Mellon in which he predicted\nthe speedy return of prosperity.\nThe stock market went up a point\nor two. The next morning the\nSecretary of the Treasury flatly\ndenied that he had talked optimis\ntically, or any other way, about\nbusiness conditions.\nThe chances are that Mr. Mellon\ndoesn\u2019t know what is going to hap\npen. He differs from the rest of\nthe wiseacres who sit on the pin\nnacle of finance because he is too\ncanny to be caught and convicted\nas a bum guesser.\n\u201cFlying\u201d Over Good Roads\nGood roads make good commun\nities, good citizens and good busi\nness. At least that is the belief of\none Cecil Hawley, and he should\nknow. For after infinite prepara\ntions Hawley, who is director of the\nTexaco National Road Report Ser\nvice, has just succeeded in estab\nlishing two transcontinental time\nsaving records \u2014speed records they\nare sometimes called. In 67 hours\nand 38 minutes he drove from New\nYork City to Los Angeles; and in 69\nhours and 20 minutes he returned.\nFrom east to west this is seventeen\nhours faster than the fastest train\ntime\nNext to the speed of a radio wave\ncomes the speed of a ray of light;\nand after that the fastest things in\nour universe are the sounds of the\nhuman voice over an electric wire\nand the wings of an airplane tra\nveling through space.\nRecently Captain Frank M.\nHawks, sitting snugly in the cock\npit of his little \u201cTexaco No. 13,\u201d\nshot across the continent in 12\nhours, 25 minutes and three seconds.\nIn eighteen months Captain Hawks\nhas cut in approximately half the\ntime necessary for an individual to\ntravel from the Pacific to the At\nlantic Ocean across the United\nStates. His highroad has been the\nhighway of the sky\u2014sometimes\nrough, but never \u201cwashed out\u201d for\nmore than an hour or so.\nCecil Hawley, in setting his two\nnew transcontinental automobile\nrecords, and also the record for the\nround-trip, had good roads over\nwhich to drive. But he says it was\ndifferent three years ago when he\nwas forced to waste seven or eight\ndays in the Southwest because rains\nhad demolished highways, and be\ncause he had no knowledge of con\nditions. Now, however, with over\n7,700 correspondents throughout\nthe country reporting to the Texaco\nNational Road Report Service, Haw\nley drives his automobile through\nthe nation\u2019s state s, counties, cities\nand towns at a rate .just a little\nslower than five times as slow as\nCaptain Hawks flies his plane. And\nCaptain Hawks sometimes flie s as\nfast as 260 miles an hour.\n\u201cGood roads make a nation great\u201d\nis an adage never too old to be new.\nPanic Buying of Feed\nThe Agricultural Department\nwarns that there is no occasion for\n\u201cpanic buying\u201d of fbeds or the sell\ning of livestock as a result of the\ndrought, and it says that farmers\nshould not hoard field stuffs or sell\nstock at sacrifice prices because of\nfear of the feed shortage. Orderly\nbuying of feeds and orderly distri\nbution is guaranteed by the Gov\nernment and the farmers all over\nthe country will be fully protected,\naccording to the Government re\nport.\nIf Farmer Prospers, Who Gets the\nMoney?\nIf a farmer becomes prosperous,\nwhat happens to the money he\nmakes? This question is answered\nby former Secretary of Agriculture\nW. M. Jardine, in the current issue\nof The Country Home.\nThe city gets it in the end, he\nsays.\nOn the face of things it appears\nthat everything else would take\ncare of itself if the farmer is given\nmore money and allowed to spend\nit as he wants, Jardine continues.\nBut experience prove s that this is\nnot necessarily true. Many families\nrelatively prosperous, move to town\nto get the benefits of the city\u2019s\nstandard of life, Jardine says. The\nprosperous farmer either sells his\nfarm or places a tenant in charge.\nIn the latter case, the farm must\nsupport two families. The new man\nhas his fortune to make out of the\nsoil. The owner spends his income\non things that deprive his farm\ncommunity not only of his money\nbut his intelligent direction. Even\nthough the owner retains direction\nof his farm, his wealth goes into\nstocks and bonds, which enrich the\ncities. Even if he stays on the\nfarm, his surplus wealth goes into\nsecurities that upbuild the cities.\nThe perennial loss of surplus wealth\nfrom the country is one of the out\nstanding causes of a barren country\nlife. It is slow to accumulate, but\nsurplus wealth can do a great deal\nstated that it porposed to carry out\nthe means of making the farm\nhome a desirable place to live, Jar\ndine declares.\nHAY STACKS\nSCATTERED\nDestructive Wind Sunday Evening\nPlays Havoc \u2014John Winters\nBarn Razed\nA heavy wind storm Sunday eve\nning, accompanied by rain, heavy\nin some places but not amounting\nto much in Mahnomen, leveled a\ngreat number of hay stacks, and\ndestroyed the big barn of John\nWinters in Rosedale. Other damage\nwas done that has not been report\ned. The storm seemed to have a\npenchant for hay stacks, of which\nthere is an unusual number in the\ncountry this year. In some places\ntrees were blown over.\nQuite a number of picnicers were\nout on the road, and some were de\nlayed several hours in getting home.\nThere was more rain in other lo\ncalities than in Mahnomen, where\nbut .24 of an inch was recorded. The\nKnights of Columbus delegates re\nturning from Bemidji found trees\nacross the road in some places.\nThe storm was general through\nout the state. Toward Thief River\nFalls all lines of communication\nwere down.\nThere was also a heavy rain Fri\nday night of last week, which varied\nin different parts of the county. The\ngovernment guage here recorded .33\nof an inch. Opinions vary as\nto the benefits of the rains to late\npotatoes, but pastures show the ef\nfects already and fall plowing will\nbe a lot pleasanter on account of\nthe moisture.\nRe-cleaning attachments for\ngrain separators and combine har\nvesters make possible the removal\nof dockage from grain at the time\nof harvesting or threshing.\nMahnomen, Minnesota, Friday, September 5, 1930\nComing Down to Earth\nFIRE DAMAGES\nPOWERPLANT\nMidnight Blaze Thursday\u2014Fire De\npartment Saves Machinery\u2014\nRunning Ag'ain\nFire broke out in the roof of the\nMahnomen power plant about 11:30\no\u2019clock Thursday night and before\nthe flames were sudued the roof\nhad been burned and the plant,\nwhich was running to full capacity,\nwas put o\u2019#, of commission. The\ntowns served by the high line run\nning north out of Twin Valley,\nMahnomen, Winger, Bejou, Fertile\nand Gary wore out of juice for a\nshort time. The fire had made much\nheadway before the department\ncould get into action, as the wood\nwork in the attic was very dry and\nburned rapidly.\nAs the wires from the generators\n-became soaked 'the switch at the\nmain plant kicked out automatical\nly. Andrew Heiberg immediately\ncalled up Mahnomen and made ar\nrangements to cut out this plant\nand supply all the power from the\nmain plant. There was a few min\nutes delay in cutting over the wires\nhere, and as soon as this was done\nthe power was again turned on.\nThis allowed the pumping station\nto again be put in operation.\nMr. Heiberg drove to Mahnomen\nimmediately after the power was\nturned on, and after looking over\nthe situation returned to Twin Val\nley, picked upa crew of men. and at\n8 the following morning had the\nwork of clearing up the debris\nstarted. Saturday night one unit of\nthe three here was again cut into\nthe line. The new roof is on, and it\nis expected that all of the units will\nbe cut in this week, There was some\nquick work done after the fire so\nthat there was little interruption in\nthe service.\nCLEM BEAULIEU\nCLAIMED BY DEATH\n(Thirteen Towns)\nBemidji, Aug. 22.\u2014Clem Beaulieu,\n87 years old, in his youth a govern\nment scout and dispatch carrier,\ndied Wednesday, August 20, at the\nRed Lake hospital. He is survived\nby six sons, five daughters and two\nsisters.\nFuneral services will be held at\nthe Catholic church at Red Lake at\n8 a. m. Friday, and interment will\nbe in the Red Lake cemetery. Mr.\nBeaulieu had lived at R-ed Lake for\nthe past 66 years.\nDuring his more active period of\nlife, Clem Beaulieu was prominent\nin Indian affairs both at Red Lake\nand at Washington, D. C. He was\nthe post treasurer 60 years ago at\nRed Lake, and had a broad fund of\nknowledge pertaining to Indian af\nfairs. He received his education in\nSt. Paul. During his youth he serv\ned the United States Government\nat Fort Ripley, where he was a\nscout and dispatch carrier.\nTwo sisters surviving are Mrs.\nMclntosh of Beaulieu, and Mrs.\nJennie Liddefburrow of St. Paul.\nSons surviving are Paul, William,\nGeorge, Alec, Charles and Joseph,\nall of Red Lake, and the daughters\nare Mrs.'Joseph Fairbanks, Mrs.\nCharles Dolson, Miss Maggie Beau\nlieu, Mrs. Adam Lucier and Mrs.\nG. W. Clifford, all of Red Lake.\nMisses Gladys Person, Alice Sol\nberg and Helen Warden left Satur\nday for Moorhead to enter the state\nteachers college. This is Misses\nSolberg\u2019s and Person\u2019s second year.\nSTORED GRAIN\nADVANCE LOANS\nSeventy Per Cent of Value Will Be\nMade to Growers In The\nNorthwest\nInstructions for obtaining ad\nvances upon elevator stored grain\nby members of the Northwest Grain\nAssociation were announced Wed\nnesday by W. J. Kuhrt, general\nmanager of the Federal Farm Board\nregional co-operative organization\nin Minneapolis, and detailed in\nstructions regarding the making of\nthese loans have been mailed to all\nmanagers of the member elevator\nassociation in the Northwest states.\nWhile the Northwest Grain asso\nciation will make loans to growers\nthrough other than member eleva\ntors, Mr. Kuhrt points out that the\ninstructions announced today are\napplicable only to local member\n,elevators of the association and are\nto be used only in the case of ele\nvator-stored grain. He state that\ndetails of the making of advance\nloans to shippers who do not belong\nto the organization will be an\nnounced at a later date, together\nwith instructions for the making of\nloans on farm-stored grain in states\nwhere a farm storage act is in force.\n\u2022Seventy Per Cent of Value\nAccording to the announcement,\nthe Northwest Grain association\nwill advance up to 70 per cent of the\nlocal value of all grain, including\nflax, based on the local card price\nexclusive of premium values. Ad\nvances on flax may not exceed a\nmaximum of $1.25 per bushel. This\nschedule will apply equally in the\ncase of ordinary stored grain and\nin the case of grain which the mem\nber wishes to pool. The interest\nrate on these advances will be 5^2\nper cent.\nTo obtain these advances, accord\ning to the instructions, the grower\nneed only sign the producer mem-\nGrain association and indorse his\nbership agreement of the Northwest\nstorage tickets over to the associa\ntion. The proceeds of the advance\nwill be paid by the local elevator\nmanager immediately upon delivery\nof the grain.\nTime of Sale\nIn the case of \u201cordinary stored\u201d\ngrain, that is, grain not pooled, Mr.\nKuhrt points out that the grower\nretains full right to determine the\ntime of sale of his grain, except in\na case where the market price falls\nto a point so as to jeopardize the\nsafety of the loan. However, where\nthe producer elects to have his\ngrain handled in a pool, he must\nwhich in turn passes over to the\nNorthwest Grain association, the\nright of determining the time of\nsale. In all cases, according to the\nannouncement, the grain must be\nsold and final settlement made to\nthe producer on or before July 1,\n1931.\nEDWARD WELTE, LENGBY\nBANKER, DIES FROM STROKE\n(Thirteen Towns)\nEdward Welte, cashier of the\nFarmers State Bank of Lengby for\nthe past fifteen years, sustained a\nstroke last week and failed to re\ncover consciousness before his death\nTuesday, August 26, at the local\nhospital.\nAlthough his health had not been\nas fromerly for several months past,\nword received that Mr. Welte could\nnot recover was a shock not only to\nthe family but to the entire district.\nHe lingered until ten o\u2019clock Tues\nday morning when he peacefully\npassed away.\nEdward Welte was bom in lowa,\nECTIVE PAGE\nOctober 28, 1879, a son of Anton and\nKaroline Welte, who moved upon a\nhomestead claim in township of\nColumbia in 1884, the year after the\nThirteen Towns were opened to\nsettlement. Both parents have been\ndead for some years. After he had\nreached young manhood, Mr. Welte\ntaught school in a number of dis\ntricts in Polk county and fifteen\nyears ago he entered the banker\u2019s\nprofession, assuming the cashier\nship of the Farmers State Bank of\nLengby, conducting a conservative\nbut successful institution during\nthese intervening years and up to\nhis recent illness.\nMr. Welte was one of an unusual\nly large family of whom there are\nliving the following: Theodore Wel\nte of Bagley; George Welte of Leng\nby; Albert Welte of Hingham, Mont;\nOtto Welte of Hinden, Sask.; Henry\nWelte of Crookston (county auditor\nof Polk county); Anna Welte (Sister\nEusebia) of Duluth. Those who have\npreceded this brother to the grave\nare Mary Magdalen Welte, who died\nwhen a child; Ida, who died Oct. 10,\n1929; William, whose death took\nplace Dec. 16, 1929; Joseph, who was\ntaken Feb. 9, 1909 and Frank, whose\ndeath took place Aug. 13, 1929. It is\nnoted that this fine family have\nhad a vast amount of grief within\nthe past thirteen months, no less\nthan four\u2014one sister and three\nbrothers\u2014being taken within a\nlittle over one year\u2019s time.\nThe remaining brothers and sis\nters have sincere sympathy in their\npresent sad bereavement.\nThe departed was a man of sterl\ning character and untiring industry.\nHe will be missed in the Lengby\ncommunity where he has held a\nprominent place for these many\nyears past.\nThe funeral will be conducted to\nday (Friday) with services at the\nhome, 1:30 and in Fridhem church,\nLengby, at two o\u2019clock.\nFORMER RESIDENTS VISIT\nFRIENDS IN MAHNOMEN\nMr. and Mrs. C. M. Helfrich and\ntwo little boys were in Mahnomen\nSunday and Monday, taking time to\ncall on a few old friends, and leav\ning for Osakis Monday morning\nwhere they were to visit Mrs. Hel\nfrich\u2019s mother. Leo Kessler, who\nhas been spending the summer at\nHebron, their home, returned with\nthem. Mr. Helfrich has had a very\nprosperous summer at Hebron,\nwhere he is operating a creamery on\nhis own account. His time was lim\nited as substitute butter makers are\nhard to get in that country. Both\nwould have liked more time here.\nSigvald Tveit joined other mem\nbers of the Ninth District Legion\nband here Saturday and went to\nthe cities. The band has special\nquarters on the grounds, and is at\ntracting a lot of attention.\nFIVE DIVISIONS\nASK INCREASES\nRequests For Next Biennium Show\nIncrease of $121,027 Over\nPresent Figures\nIncrease of $121,027 for the next\nbiennium is requested in proposed\nbudgets by five divisions of the\nstate government submitted this\nweek to A. J. Peterson, state com\nmissioner of personnel.\nThe departments and divisions,\nincluding the Minnesota tax com\nmission, state banking division and\nthe department of education, re\nquest a total of $956,537 for the next\ntwo years compared with a budget\nallowance of $835,510 granted by the\nlast legislature for the present bien\nnium.\nThe largest request submitted so\nfar is that of the department of\neducation which asks $382,783 com\npared with $352,330 granted for this\nbiennium.\nThe state banking division re\nquests $284,495 for the next bien\nnium compared with $256,500 ap\nproved by the last legislature. The\nincrease here is because of a lower\nbalance in funds than two years\nago.\nThe Minnesota Tax Commission\nrequests $119,606 for the next two\nyears compared with an appropria\ntion of $87,190 granted by the last\nlegislature for the present biennium\nThe tourists division of the state\ndepartment of conservation re\nquests SIOO,OOO to be used in adver\ntising the state\u2019s natural resources.\nTwo years ago the legislature grant\ned $75,000.\nThe securities division requests\n$69,-653 compared with an appro\npriation two years ago of $64,490.\nHUNTING LAWS IN\nSTATE TO CHANGE\nRegulations Will Comply With U.\nS. Rules\u2014Cut Number\nof Birds\nMinnesota is changing its hunting\nlaws to conform with federal stat\nutes, which reduce the number of\nmigratory birds a hunter may have\nin his possession at one time,\nGeorge W. McCullough, state com\nmissioner of game and fish, an\nnounced Wednesday, according to\nthe Minneapolis Journal.\nUnder the Minnesota law, the\npossession limit is 36 birds. The\nfederal law provides that only 30\nbirds can be in the possession of\none person. The Minnesota law\nwill be changed to meet this re\nquirement, Mr. McCullough said.\nUnder the federal regulations, the\ndaily limit on ducks will be changed\nfrom 25 to 15. The Minnesota daily\nlimit of 12 will remain unchanged.\nThe federal daily limit on geese is\nreduced from eight to four, with\npossesion placed at eight. The\nstate limit is now five and will be\nreplaced by the federal rule, but the\npossession limit of five birds re\nmains effective.\nThe Minnesota hunting season\nopens September 16. Mr. McCul\nlough said that effort will be made\nat the next state legislative session\nto make the state law conform with\nthe federal statutes.\nINFANTILE PARALYSIS\nSt. Paul, Minnesota \u2014The ques\ntions what is the serum treatment\nfor poliomyelitis? How effective is\nit? When should it be administer\ned? Are answered briefly in today\u2019s\nbulletin from the Minnesota State\nMedical Association.\nNo contagious disease of children\nis so feared and dreaded as this\none, generally known as infantile\nparalysis.\nThe fact that there is a treatment\nwhich offers great hope of the pre\nventing the development of the\nparalysis that often follows, is cited\nas one of the glories of modern\nmedical science.\nThere are still difficulties in the\nway involved chiefly in securing the\nserum used and administering it at\nthe precise moment when it will be\neffective. But the fact that, pro\nperly used, it has shown excellent\nresults in a sign, in the opinion of\nthe medical association experts that\nthe first and most difficult step has\nalready been achieved in the even\ntual conquest of the disease.\nA time may come when poliomy\nelitis will be as completely subdued,\nmedically, as diptheria now is. In\nthe meantime it has been discover\ned and well authenticated that the\nuse of a blood serum from a patient\nwho has recovered from the disease,\nintra-muscularly will limit its\ncourse and, if administered soon\nenough will usually prevent the\nsubsequent destruction of nerve\ncells that means paralysis.\nThe successful use of this serum\ndepends upon an early diagnosis in\nthe pre-paralytic stage which only\nthe doctor can do. Any illness with\nfever, a slight stiffness of the neck,\nheadache and gastro-intestinal dis\nturbances should be reported to the\ndoctor immediately, particularly in\nsummer when poliomyelitis is pre\nvalent. The disease presents a fair\nly typical picture by which the doc\ntor can tell what to expect.\nThe fact that there are many\ncases of \u201cpolio\u201d that do not develop\nthe typical paralysis and therefore\nare neither diagnosed nor isolated\nmakes control of the disease diffi\ncult.\nFor all parents, the things to re\nmember are:\nProtect your children by cleanli\nness and care from infections of all\nsorts.\nKeep them away from anyone\nwho is sick.\nCall the doctor immediately if\nthey are sick themselves. Probably\nit won\u2019t be poliomyelitis. But if it\nis, the doctor will know and he will\nbe able to administer this serum\ntreatment at the time when it will\nbe most effective in preventing the\ndread paralysis of the disease.\nMr. and Mrs. John Holtorf, Sr.,\nand son, Fred, and Miss Nellie\nMeyer returned Tuesday afternoon\nafter a week\u2019s trip through the\nnorthern part of the state. They\nvisited at the home of their son,\nHarry, 'and family at Ah-Gwan-\nChing, Minnesota. They also visit\ned at the August Holtorf home at\nMahnomen and the Fred Zilmer\nhome at Waite Park. They stated\nthat the territory in that region\nwas even slightly more dry than\nhere. They reported a very enjoy\nable trip.\u2014Dodge Center Star.\nNumber 17","height":"26130","width":"18675"}}
